ign-language Versions in Postwar Danish informational film -- t12. A Sámi in Hollywood: Nils Gaup’s Transnational and Generic Negotiations -- t13. “There is no Elsewhere!”: Stories of Race, Decolonization, and Global Connectivity in Göran Hugo Olsson’s Documentaries -- t14. Aki Kaurismäki’s Finno-French Connections and Other Transcultural Elsewheres -- t15. Nordic Noir as a Calling Card: The International Careers of Danish Film and Television Talent in the 2010s -- tPART III. CONTACT ZONES -- t16. Paris Looks to the North: Swedish Silent Film and the Emergence of Cinephilia -- t17. Celebrated, Contested, Criticized: Anita Ekberg, a Swedish Sex Goddess in Hollywood -- t18. The Finnish Cinema Colony in North America, 1938−1941 -- t19. The Transnational Politics of Lars von Trier’s and Thomas Vinterberg’s “Amerika” -- t20. The Globalization of the Danish Documentary: Creative Collaboration and Modes of Global Documentaries -- t21. Elsewheres of Healing: Trans-Indigenous Spaces in Elle-Máijá Apiniskim Tailfeathers’ Bihttoš -- t22. Denmark beyond Denmark: Soft Power, Talent Development, and Filmmaking in the Middle East -- tPART IV. REVISITATIONS -- t23. Dreyer’s Jeanne d’Arc at the Cinéma d’Essai: Cinephiliac and Political Passions in 1950s Paris -- t24. I Am Curious (Yellow) as Sex Education in the USA -- t25. Transnational Cinefeminism of the 1970s and Mai Zetterling’s Documentary Elsewheres -- t26. The Serpent’s Egg: Ingmar Bergman’s Exilic Elsewheres in 1970s New German and New Hollywood Cinema -- t27. Bridging Places, Media, and Traditions: Lasse Hallström’s Chronotopes -- t28. Criminal Undertakings: Nicolas Winding Refn, European Film Aesthetics, and Hollywood Genre Cinema -- t29. The Cinematic Kon-Tiki Expeditions: Realism, Spectacle, and the Migration of Nordic Cinema -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aA globalized history of Nordic film cultures in a transnational contextIntroduces the concept of “Elsewheres” and “Cinemas of Elsewhere” – of value for many small national film culturesPromotes an understanding of Scandinavian cinemas as world cinemasExamines overlooked and little-known aspects of how Nordic cinemas have been funded, produced, circulated, received, appropriated and re-imagined outside of ScandinaviaAddresses cinemas of exile, diaspora, migration, emigration and immigrationIntegrates examples of early and silent cinema, popular cinema, art cinema, documentary, shorts, experimental film, expanded media, the avant-garde, video art, music videos, ethnography, television and digital representationEngages with questions of colonialism, gender, multi-lingualism, inter- and cross-cultural representation, film practice in the diaspora and visual anthropologyEngages with Indigenous cinemas of the NorthNordic Film Cultures and Cinemas of Elsewhere introduces a new concept to Nordic film studies as well as to other small national, transnational and world cinema traditions. Examining overlooked ‘elsewheres’, the book presents Nordic cinemas as international, cosmopolitan, diasporic and geographically dispersed, from their beginnings in the early silent period to their present 21st-century dynamics. Exploring both canonical works by directors like Ingmar Bergman and Lars von Trier, as well as a wide range of unknown or overlooked narratives of movement, synthesis and resistance, the book offers a new model of inquiry into a multi-varied Scandinavian cultural lineage, and into small nation and pan-regional world cinemas.ContributorsJulie K. Allen, Brigham Young University Linda Badley, Middle Tennessee State UniversityAna Bento-Ribeiro, Paris Nanterre UniversityBenjamin Bigelow, University of Minnesota, Twin Cities Mats Bjorkin, University of GothenburgIb Bondebjerg, University of CopenhagenPatrick Ellis, Georgia Institute of Technology Kim Khavar Fahlstedt, Uppsala University Annie Fee, University of OsloSaniya Lee Ghan